ial-reform";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:67:"Restoring Momentum in Transatlantic Cooperation on Financial Reform";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5492:"<div>
	<img src="http://www.brookings.edu/~/media/events/2013/7/15%20transatlantic%20cooperation%20financial%20reform/barnier_elliott/barnier_elliott_16x9.jpg?w=120" alt="European Union Commissioner for Internal Market and Services Michel Barnier with Douglas Elliott" border="0" /><br /><h4>
		Event Information
	</h4><div>
		<p>July 15, 2013<br />8:30 AM - 9:30 AM EDT</p><p>Falk Auditorium<br/>Brookings Institution<br/>1775 Massachusetts Avenue, N.W.<br/>Washington, DC 20036</p>
	</div><a href="http://www.cvent.com/d/8cqh3q/4W">Register for the Event</a><br /><p><img style="width: 125px; float: left; height: 125px; margin-right: 10px;" alt="European Union Commissioner for Internal Market and Services Michel Barnier speaks at Brookings, July 15, 2013" src="http://www.brookings.edu/~/media/Events/2013/7/15 transatlantic cooperation financial reform/barnier/barnier_1x1.jpg" />On July 15, the Initiative on Business and Public Policy (IBPP) at the Brookings Institution hosted a discussion on the status of cooperation across the Atlantic on financial regulatory reform, featuring remarks by European Union Commissioner for Internal Market and Services Michel Barnier, who directs Europe&rsquo;s efforts. Commissioner Barnier presented his views on how best to accelerate progress towards genuine financial stability. Brookings Fellow Douglas Elliott hosted the discussion and moderated a question and answer period.</p>
<p>Barnier began his remarks by describing how the European Union and the United States came to an agreement about how to regulate cross-border swaps at the G20 summit in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, three and a half years ago. This &ldquo;ambitious global regulatory reform of the swaps markets&rdquo; set out to do three strategic tasks:</p>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Clearing:</strong> To reduce risk in our financial firms and system by clearing all standardized swaps through central counterparties.<br />
    &nbsp;</li>
    <li><strong>Transparency:</strong> To shed light on this opaque market and report all trades to trade repositories. We need to know where risk is building up in the system.<br />
    &nbsp;</li>
    <li><strong>Trading:</strong> Where appropriate, to move standardized swaps to venues to increase market transparency</li>
</ol>
<p>Barnier compared uncoordinated cross-border regulations between the United States and the European Union to &ldquo;squeezing a bar of soap with wet hands: it slips from your hands. Trades will be re-booked. Markets will fragment. The G20 reform objectives will not be met.&rdquo; Barnier noted that 70% of all global economic transactions take place between the United States and the European Union nations. For this reason, he argued that the United States and European Union need to &ldquo;lead by example&rdquo; by carrying out necessary economic reforms to meet G20 commitments &ldquo;rigorously and sensibly.&rdquo; </p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img style="width: 500px; height: 282px;" alt="European Union Commissioner for Internal Market and Services Michel Barnier with Douglas Elliott" src="http://www.brookings.edu/~/media/Events/2013/7/15 transatlantic cooperation financial reform/barnier_elliott/barnier_elliott_16x9.jpg" /><br />
<br />
<span style="font-size: 11px;">European Union Commissioner for Internal Market and Services Michel Barnier with Douglas Elliott<br />
(Photo by Chris Maddaloni)</span></p>
<p>Barnier described the trade negotiations between the European Union and the United States that began last week as focused on &ldquo;growth and leadership,&rdquo; which are imperative to cultivating new jobs in each sovereign nation, as well as finding solutions to trade predicaments that cannot be found through multilateral discussions. Barnier argued that the &ldquo;barriers to EU-US trade and investment are in the details of regulatory policy,&rdquo; and &ldquo;regulatory barriers can block trade outright. Make it too expensive to be viable. Fragment global markets. Or just act as a drag on overall economic efficiency.&rdquo; Mitigating these barriers through regulatory reform will effectively protect the European Union and the U.S. economies from risks to their citizens and financial security.</p>
<p>To conclude his remarks, Barnier noted that the fundamental component of transatlantic trade reform is the joint leadership between the United States and the European Union. He believes &ldquo;our financial sectors know no borders. They are intertwined and interdependent.&rdquo; By reflecting on the agreement on swaps, Commissioner Barnier believes that the United States and European Union can create a dynamic bond that will &ldquo;raise the bar in tomorrow&rsquo;s world of financial regulation.&rdquo;</p><h4>
